    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the help. i'll look into the fertilizer. do you know how i can check if the soil pH is actually the problem though? like is there a specific way to test it so i know for sure if the nitrogen isnt getting through?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you can test the soil pH using a simple kit that measures acidity levels, which is crucial because tomatoes need a pH between 6.0 and 6.8 to absorb nutrients effectively. If your soil is too acidic or alkaline, even the best nitrogen fertilizer won't be able to reach the plant's roots. You can buy a digital meter or a test strip set from a garden center to get an accurate reading before applying more fertilizer. It's worth noting that if the pH is off, you might need to add lime to raise it or sulfur to lower it, rather than just feeding the plants. Always test a few different spots in your garden to get a true average.",
